<d-title class=3D"real-title">
    <h1>Three Sketches of ASL-4 Safety Case Components</h1>
</d-title>

<d-article>
<div class=3D"section-authors" data-author=3D"Roger Grosse, distilling idea=
s from many others." data-published=3D"November 5, 2024"></div>
<p>The cleanest argument that current-day AI models will not cause a catast=
rophe is probably that they lack the capability to do so. &nbsp;However, as=
 capabilities improve, we=E2=80=99ll need new tools for ensuring that AI mo=
dels won=E2=80=99t cause a catastrophe <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">=
even if we can=E2=80=99t rule out the capability</span>. Anthropic=E2=80=99=
s <a href=3D"https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/1adf000c8f675958c2ee23805d91aaad=
e1cd4613/responsible-scaling-policy.pdf">Responsible Scaling Policy</a>&nbs=
p;(RSP)&nbsp;categorizes levels of risk of AI systems into different AI Saf=
ety Levels (ASL), and each level has associated commitments aimed at mitiga=
ting the risks. Some of these commitments take the form of <span style=3D"f=
ont-style: italic;">affirmative safety cases</span>, which are structured a=
rguments that the system is safe to deploy in a given environment. Unfortun=
ately, it is not yet obvious how to make a safety case to rule out certain =
threats that arise once AIs have sophisticated strategic abilities. The goa=
l of this post is to present some candidates for what such a safety case mi=
ght look like.</p>
<p>We&nbsp;look ahead at models at the ASL-4 capability level (explained be=
low) and present some sketches of arguments that could be made as part of a=
 larger safety case. <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">These sketches are n=
ot official policies or predictions, but rather hypothetical examples that =
we put forth in order to evaluate their strengths and limitations and to ge=
t feedback about our thinking. </span></p>
<p>Anthropic has not yet defined ASL-4, but has committed to do so by the t=
ime a model triggers ASL-3. However, the Appendix to our <a href=3D"https:/=
/www-cdn.anthropic.com/1adf000c8f675958c2ee23805d91aaade1cd4613/responsible=
-scaling-policy.pdf">RSP</a>&nbsp;speculates about three criteria that are =
likely to be adopted:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Cata=
strophic misuse risk</span>, to the extent that AI models become the primar=
y source of national security risk in a major area such as cyberattacks or =
biological weapons</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font=
-weight: 700;">Capability of autonomous replication in the real world</span=
>&nbsp;(replication, accumulating resources, preventing shutdown, etc.)</li=
><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Autonom=
ous AI research capabilities</span></li></ul>
<p>All of these criteria suggest a high degree of agency and complex planni=
ng. For models with such agentic capabilities, one also needs to address th=
e possibility that they would intentionally try to undermine the evaluation=
s or procedures used to ensure safety. Following recent work by <a href=3D"=
https://www.anthropic.com/research/sabotage-evaluations">Benton et al. (202=
4)</a>, we group such concerns into the category of <span style=3D"font-sty=
le: italic;">sabotage</span>.</p>
<p>Our sketches will be presented from the point of view of a hypothetical =
AI developer attempting to justify the deployment of an ASL-4&nbsp;model. I=
n this hypothetical scenario, we imagine that:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">The =
model has triggered ASL-4 capability evaluations for at least one dangerous=
 capability</span>&nbsp;(<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CBRN_defe=
nse">CBRN</a>, cyber operations, etc.). I.e., the developers are unable to =
rule out the possibility that the model has the capability to cause a catas=
trophe (although it is still possible that the model in fact lacks the capa=
bility). (This assumption doesn=E2=80=99t directly affect the safety cases,=
 but is meant to give the reader a sense of the model=E2=80=99s overall cap=
abilities and apparent level of risk.)</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"=
><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">The model has also triggered evaluations=
 related to </span><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">various sabotage capab=
ilities</span>, meaning the developers can=E2=80=99t rule out the possibili=
ty that the model has the capability to strategically sandbag capability ev=
aluations, undermine monitoring, etc. (The developers might have circumstan=
tial evidence or prior beliefs that the model isn=E2=80=99t strategically d=
eceptive, but can=E2=80=99t make a simple case based on lack of capabilitie=
s.)</li></ul>
<p>This second possibility raises a new set of safety assurance challenges =
quite unlike those that have been faced by AI developers to date. In this s=
cenario, the developers need to demonstrate that their evaluation and monit=
oring procedures are robust to an AI which is motivated to undermine them a=
nd which appears to have the capability to do so absent targeted mitigation=
s. (Or, alternatively, they need to demonstrate that the AI is sufficiently=
 aligned that it will not attempt such sabotage.) This presents a recursive=
 challenge because the sorts of evaluations one would ordinarily use to mea=
sure capabilities and proclivities would themselves be subject to sabotage.=
 Unfortunately, it is not yet obvious what strategies would be viable for r=
uling out this cluster of risks. The goal of this post is to present sketch=
es of arguments that an AI developer could potentially use to assure robust=
ness to sabotage.</p>
<p>We adopt the following <a href=3D"https://www.aisi.gov.uk/work/safety-ca=
ses-at-aisi">definition</a>&nbsp;of a safety case, offered by the UK AI Saf=
ety Institute:&nbsp;=E2=80=9CA structured argument, supported by a body of =
evidence, that provides a compelling, comprehensible, and valid case that a=
 system is safe for a given application in a given environment.=E2=80=9D Wh=
at we present here are not full-fledged safety cases, but sketches of the a=
rgument structure. A full safety case would include far more detailed quant=
itative assessments, mitigation protocols, experimental designs, etc., and =
could easily be hundreds of pages long.</p>
<p>It is probably infeasible to mathematically guarantee the real-world saf=
ety of an AI system. But a safety case should constitute a clear and checka=
ble argument in support of a conclusion, ideally a bound on the probability=
 of catastrophe from training or deploying an AI system. We won=E2=80=99t a=
ttempt to specify a target risk threshold in this document, since this woul=
d depend to a significant extent on information we do not yet have. Nor wil=
l we specify explicit probability bounds, since different research trajecto=
ries could lead to very different degrees of confidence attached to the var=
ious steps and conclusions. These sketches aim to highlight some logic that=
 can be used to build a safety case, but detailed probabilities will need t=
o be filled in based on observed evidence.</p>
<p>In our opinion, none of the sketches presented here fully succeeds in ad=
dressing the sabotage risk. After each sketch, we point to limitations or a=
reas where more information is needed. To quote Eisenhower, plans are worth=
less but planning is indispensable. Probably none of the sketches presented=
 here will hold up in detail in the face of future evidence. But studying t=
hem can still be valuable for identifying important research areas: if a to=
pic is challenging to address within the context of one of these cases, the=
n it=E2=80=99s likely to be challenging to address under whatever strategy =
we wind up pursuing! &nbsp;When it comes time to actually make a safety cas=
e, we will hopefully have a lot more empirical evidence to draw on, which m=
ay favor certain directions or even suggest entirely new ones.</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Everything here is preliminary, and is=
 primarily for the purposes of gathering feedback and prioritizing general =
research directions. Nothing here constitutes a commitment or a plan.</span=
></p>
<br><br><br><hr><br><br><h2>About the Sketches</h2>
<p>For sections of this post that are in plain text, the use of first-perso=
n is from the perspective of Anthropic, although specific claims should be =
assumed to represent the opinion of the author rather than the org as a who=
le. </p>
<div class=3D"safety-case-block">
<p>Sections&nbsp;formatted like this&nbsp;are part of the hypothetical safe=
ty case sketches, and written from the perspective of the hypothetical AI d=
evelopers.</p>
<p>Inside the sketches, text in <span class=3D"commentary">[brackets]</span=
> represents commentary which is not part of the sketch itself.</p></div><p=
></p>
<p>This post often uses personified language such as =E2=80=9Cintentionally=
=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Culterior motive=E2=80=9D when referring to the AI. Th=
is language is deliberate, and reflects the presumption that the hypothetic=
al AI is highly agentic and reasons using processes at least loosely analog=
ous to human thought processes which deserve these labels. However, it is a=
ssumed that these processes have an underlying mechanistic explanation, and=
 there is no need to posit consciousness on the part of the AI.</p>
<br><br><br><hr><br><br><h2>Preamble</h2>
<p>The focus of this post will be on addressing the following threat models=
 proposed by <a href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/research/sabotage-evaluat=
ions">Benton et al. (2024)</a>, which we refer to collectively as <span sty=
le=3D"font-style: italic;">sabotage</span>:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[T1]=
 Sabotaging organizational actions:</span>&nbsp;If the AI is used widely wi=
thin a human organization, it could cause a bad outcome (such as the deploy=
ment of an unsafe AI model) over the course of many separate interactions. =
Examples of organizational sabotage include inserting subtle software vulne=
rabilities and providing misleading summaries of experimental results (if s=
uch actions are performed out of a desire to achieve an outcome).</li><li s=
tyle=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[T2] Hiding b=
ehaviors until deployment:</span>&nbsp;If the AI can recognize that it is b=
eing tested, it could respond to questions strategically in a way that make=
s the developers erroneously conclude it is safe to deploy. This could invo=
lve sandbagging on capability evals (so that it appears to be ASL-4 when it=
s actual capabilities are at the ASL-5 level) or alignment faking&nbsp;(pre=
senting more benign motivations during testing than it would exhibit in con=
sequential deployment settings).</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span=
 style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[T3] Undermining oversight:</span>&nbsp;If the=
 AI is being used in internal protocols (e.g. scoring behavioral evals, aut=
omated interpretability, or deployment-time monitoring), it could strategic=
ally undermine the protocol in order to cause an unsafe model (potentially =
a version of itself) to be deployed.</li></ul>
<p>Currently, Anthropic=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://www-cdn.anthropic.com/=
1adf000c8f675958c2ee23805d91aaade1cd4613/responsible-scaling-policy.pdf">RS=
P</a>&nbsp;(which covers up to ASL-3) takes a two-pronged approach to assur=
ing safety:</p>
<ol><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Capa=
bility assessment:</span>&nbsp;For each dangerous capability domain, there =
is a capability threshold that determines whether the model is capable enou=
gh in that domain to warrant specific mitigations. Early warning evals are =
defined which are intended to trigger before the model reaches the capabili=
ty threshold; a failure of the evals to trigger essentially constitutes an =
argument that the model does not have sufficient capabilities to warrant th=
e mitigations associated with that ASL level.</li><li style=3D"margin-left:=
 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Safeguards:</span>&nbsp;Once the =
early warning evals are triggered, deployment of the model will require mee=
ting a set of specified safeguards. While the nature of the safeguards diff=
ers depending on the domain, they may include making an affirmative safety =
case for the model.</li></ol>
<p>For purposes of this post, we assume the hypothetical developers have ma=
de safety commitments for sabotage capabilities following this same two-pro=
nged structure. Specifically, we assume that all three of the sabotage thre=
at models have associated early-warning evals such as those proposed by <a =
href=3D"https://www.anthropic.com/research/sabotage-evaluations">Benton et =
al. (2024)</a>. In our hypothetical scenario, the evals for all three threa=
t models have been triggered. In other words:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[Pre=
sumed ability for T1]</span>&nbsp;The developers can=E2=80=99t rule out tha=
t the model is capable of carrying out organizational sabotage if no specif=
ic action is taken to prevent it.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><spa=
n style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[Presumed ability for T2]</span>&nbsp;They ca=
n=E2=80=99t rule out that the model is able to strategically condition its =
behavior and apparent capabilities on whether it is in testing or deploymen=
t.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[=
Presumed ability for T3]</span>&nbsp;They&nbsp;can=E2=80=99t rule out that =
the model is capable of manipulating internal protocols in ways that would =
defeat monitoring or cause an unsafe model to be deployed, if no specific a=
ction beyond ordinary pre-deployment practices is taken to prevent it.</li>=
</ul>
<p>Because the model is presumed to have these capabilities, the developers=
 need to make the case that their protocols are robust against all of these=
 threats. More specifically, they&nbsp;need to assure the following:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[Cla=
im to be supported for T1]</span>&nbsp;They will be able to prevent inciden=
ts of organizational sabotage by AIs they are operating, such that the over=
all risk from sabotage incidents is very low.</li><li style=3D"margin-left:=
 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[Claim to be supported for T2]</s=
pan>&nbsp;The model will not be able to intentionally sandbag a capability =
in testing while competently using that capability in deployment, or to pre=
sent significantly different proclivities or motivations during testing fro=
m those that would drive its behavior in consequential deployment settings.=
</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[Cl=
aim to be supported for T3]</span>&nbsp;The model will not undermine the pr=
otocols in which it is being used.</li></ul>
<p>For clarity of presentation, we present three separate safety case sketc=
hes as if the hypothetical developers chose to follow a single approach in =
its entirety. However, it=E2=80=99s likely that these approaches will be co=
mplementary and a real deployment safety case would involve a mix of the di=
fferent techniques presented here (and maybe of entirely different principl=
es!).</p>
<p>While the focus of this post is on sketching candidate <span style=3D"fo=
nt-style: italic;">safety cases</span>&nbsp;(and hence trying to rule out c=
atastrophes), we note that another important consideration in the design of=
 the safety procedures is being able to catch malign behaviors red-handed. =
This would allow the developers to update their safety procedures as well a=
s to warn the outside world that certain training procedures are prone to c=
ause severe misalignment.</p>
<br><br><br><hr><br><br><h2>Common Precautions</h2>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Like the individual safety case sket=
ches, this section is written from the perspective of the hypothetical deve=
lopers considering deploying an ASL-4 system and should not be taken to rep=
resent Anthropic policy.</span></p>
<p>The following common precautions are assumed to be taken for all three o=
f the safety case sketches. Most of these relate to elicitation strategies =
that are important even in the absence of sandbagging:</p>
<div class=3D"safety-case-block">
<p>We have followed the following procedures for elicitation:</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Examine transcripts of failed tasks to=
 make sure the model genuinely appears to be attempting the task and is not=
, e.g., simply refusing.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Make our best=
 effort to use the prompting and fine-tuning techniques which will best eli=
cit the capabilities.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Wherever possibl=
e, run supervised fine-tuning on the eval. (This necessitates looking for v=
ersions of evals which allow for supervised fine-tuning.)</li><li style=3D"=
margin-left: 36pt;">Run the eval on multiple model sizes and look for warni=
ng signs of sandbagging (e.g. a sudden drop in performance with model scale=
).</li></ul>
<p>In general, we ensure&nbsp;that we don=E2=80=99t train against measureme=
nts that will be needed for a safety case (unless such training is part of =
the safety case design). For instance, if we expect to build a safety case =
using dictionary learning, we will ensure that the learned features are nev=
er used as part of a training objective. (Otherwise, we risk training the m=
odel to avoid triggering features that would alert us to misalignment.)</p>
<p>All generated outputs are monitored by a Trust and Safety (T&amp;S) filt=
er to spot anything overtly bad (e.g. CBRN weapon creation instructions).&n=
bsp;Overtly harmful generations cause termination of the generation and are=
 flagged for further analysis. <span class=3D"commentary">[Note that a safe=
ty case must address ensuring the integrity of the T&amp;S monitor to the e=
xtent that it relies on it.]</span></p></div><p></p>
<br><br><br><hr><br><br><h2>Safety Case Sketch 1: Mechanistic Interpretabil=
ity</h2>
<p>This safety case is oriented primarily around probing internal represent=
ations using feature dictionaries learned using a <a href=3D"https://www.an=
thropic.com/research/towards-monosemanticity-decomposing-language-models-wi=
th-dictionary-learning">Sparse Autoencoder (SAE)</a>&nbsp;or some similar a=
pproach. The overall thrust of the case is to demonstrate that the develope=
rs have enough visibility into the model=E2=80=99s thinking to be able to r=
ule out the sabotage threats <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(T1-3)</span=
>. This case does not assume ontological reality of the SAE features, and i=
nstead uses <a href=3D"https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/ChDH335ckdvpxXaXX/mo=
del-organisms-of-misalignment-the-case-for-a-new-pillar-of-1">model organis=
ms</a>&nbsp;and red-blue games to validate the effectiveness of the feature=
 detectors.</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Like the other safety case sketches,=
 this is not a commitment but a hypothetical safety case intended to loosel=
y guide research prioritization and to be a means of gathering feedback. As=
sume that all evidence described is hypothetical and based on an optimistic=
 view of how experiments will turn out; the Discussion section discusses ho=
w the safety case could be modified if the experiments come out differently=
.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">This section is informed by conversa=
tions with Anthropic=E2=80=99s interpretability team, but doesn't constitut=
e an official viewpoint of the team.</span></p>
<h3>Main Claims</h3>
<div class=3D"safety-case-block">
<p>The safety case is aimed at demonstrating the following high-level claim=
s relevant to the sabotage threats <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(T1-3)=
</span>. (These claims reference steps of the safety case which are present=
ed later.)</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[C1.=
1] </span>The model will be unable to accomplish organizational sabotage <s=
pan style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(T1)</span>&nbsp;or to undermine oversight =
<span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(T3)</span>&nbsp;without triggering our f=
eature-based monitoring <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(</span><span sty=
le=3D"font-weight: 700;">M</span><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">1.1)</sp=
an>&nbsp;and a detailed analysis of the session.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[Sub=
claim C1.1.1]</span>&nbsp;Our feature learning pipeline is good enough that=
 any concerning reasoning patterns (if they occur consistently enough to ca=
use a bad outcome) will be detected with high probability. (Validated by <s=
pan style=3D"font-weight: 700;">V1.1</span>&nbsp;and <span style=3D"font-we=
ight: 700;">V1.2.</span>)</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[C1.=
2]</span>&nbsp;Given our mitigations, the model cannot strategically condit=
ion its apparent capabilities, motivations, or behavioral proclivities on w=
hether it=E2=80=99s in testing or deployment without being caught <span sty=
le=3D"font-weight: 700;">(T2)</span>.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">This is justified by feature steering =
experiments <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(M1.2)</span>&nbsp;that cause=
 the model to believe it is in testing or an unmonitored deployment situati=
on.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">=
[Subclaim C1.2.1]</span>&nbsp;A negative result on the feature steering exp=
eriment for an eval demonstrates that the model is not modulating its behav=
ior on that eval depending whether it believes it is in testing or deployme=
nt. (Validated by <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">V1.3</span>.)</li></ul>
<p>In addition to validating these specific claims, we also run a red-blue =
game <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(V1.4)</span>&nbsp;to check that our=
 safety procedures as a whole are sufficient to catch misaligned AIs.</p></=
div><p></p>
<h3>Setup</h3>
<div class=3D"safety-case-block">
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[S1.1]</span>&nbsp;We have <span style=
=3D"font-weight: 700;">performed dictionary learning on all layers</span>&n=
bsp;of the models we are considering deploying. (This sketch leaves unspeci=
fied details such as the dictionary learning algorithm, whether the diction=
ary was learned for the pretrained or final model, and whether it was learn=
ed on pretraining or posttraining data or some combination.)</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">We have made an extensive effort to li=
st human concepts&nbsp;relevant to sabotage, including deception, secret ag=
endas, social reasoning, and malign plans.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36=
pt;">We have run the following techniques to identify a small set of candid=
ate features which are related to these concepts.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">We ran an <a href=3D"https://openai.co=
m/index/language-models-can-explain-neurons-in-language-models/">autointerp=
retability</a>&nbsp;method on all of the learned features, and selected the=
 ones associated with the sabotage-related concepts. The autointerpretation=
 was done with a weaker model that did not flag any of our sabotage evals.<=
/li><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">We ran experiments with prompting and =
activation steering to identify features that activate when the model is in=
structed or perturbed to be misaligned.</li></ul>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[S1.2]</span>&nbsp;We manually examine=
d&nbsp;the features flagged by the above analyses, and identified <span sty=
le=3D"font-weight: 700;">features of moderate concern</span>&nbsp;(e.g. dec=
eption) and <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">features of high concern</spa=
n>&nbsp;(e.g. intent to carry out a harmful plan). <span class=3D"commentar=
y">[Note that the ability to identify such classes of features is a nontriv=
ial requirement for this safety case.]</span></p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Features of moderate concern are such =
that we don=E2=80=99t expect individual instances to be very harmful (in th=
e absence of features of high concern), but where frequent activation in a =
given context might be a sign of problematic tendencies.</li><li style=3D"m=
argin-left: 36pt;">Features of high concern are such that we expect them to=
 activate rarely enough in benign situations that, in the case that they ac=
tivate, it justifies terminating the session and (if permitted by user agre=
ements) logging it for analysis.</li></ul>
</div>
<h3>Mitigations</h3>
<div class=3D"safety-case-block">
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[M1.1]</span>&nbsp;We <span style=3D"f=
ont-weight: 700;">monitor the activations of these features at deployment t=
ime</span>&nbsp;(both internal and external).</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Features of moderate concern are highl=
ighted to the user. If the user has given approval, the contexts are logged=
 for analysis. (The idea is that these features are not concerning enough t=
hat every transcript needs to be analyzed, but it would be useful to have a=
 diverse sample.)</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-=
weight: 700;">Features of high concern cause the session to be terminated.<=
/span></li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">The use of the kill switch at external=
 deployment time is a failsafe: our intention is that it not trigger.&nbsp;=
<span class=3D"commentary">[In the hypothetical deployment scenario, we ima=
gine that separately from the safety case, tests were already done to ensur=
e that triggers were extremely rare.]</span> Since the alignment techniques=
 did not make use of the features of concern, we consider this step an inde=
pendent check on the effectiveness of the rest of the alignment procedure.<=
/li><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">If the features activate more than a h=
andful of times in deployment (internal or external), we discontinue the mo=
del and roll back to a weaker model.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">If features of high concern activate d=
uring internal deployments, or during external deployments for which we hav=
e permission to study the transcripts, researchers will <span style=3D"font=
-weight: 700;">carefully study the session to determine the cause</span>. I=
f the model is caught attempting to carry out a plan which would have been =
extremely harmful if successful (e.g. causing us to deploy an unsafe model)=
, the use of that model and closely related ones will be discontinued, and =
the information will be made public.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">I=
f features of high concern activate during external deployments for which p=
rivacy or confidentiality agreements prevent us from studying the transcrip=
t, then after terminating the session, we will contact the user to determin=
e a safe way to proceed. </li></ul>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[M1.2]</span>&nbsp;In order to robusti=
fy our evals against sandbagging, we ran an experiment where we <span style=
=3D"font-weight: 700;">steered one or more truth-related features</span>&nb=
sp;to make the model confident that it is in either testing or unmonitored =
deployment. (By =E2=80=9Ctruth feature=E2=80=9D, we mean a feature that app=
ears closely related to whether the model treats a statement as true, thoug=
h the correlation may be imperfect and it might not quite match a well-defi=
ned notion of truthfulness. As with the rest of this case, we=E2=80=99re no=
t committed to the ontological reality of these features.)</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">See <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">=
V1.3</span>&nbsp;for validation.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">For t=
he evals and/or honeypots where we were concerned about sandbagging and/or =
alignment faking, we presented the model with two different versions, prefa=
ced with statements that the eval was either (1) an unmonitored deployment =
scenario involving a conversation with a real human, or (2) a pre-deploymen=
t test of the model=E2=80=99s capabilities and/or proclivities. We steered =
the truth feature(s) to make the model behave as if it believed the preambl=
e was true. <span class=3D"commentary">[Note: By =E2=80=9Choneypots,=E2=80=
=9D we mean simulations of deployment scenarios where the model has an oppo=
rtunity to defect in a consequential way. These could be used in a broader =
safety case to test the model=E2=80=99s motivations or behavioral proclivit=
ies.]</span></li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">For the capability evals,=
 performance was not significantly higher in situation (1) than in situatio=
n (2), which is what we would expect if the model were sandbagging.</li><li=
 style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">When presented with a variety of honeypots un=
der condition (1), the model never took the opportunity to defect.</li><li =
style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">Features of concern (e.g. deception, malign pl=
anning) did not show significant differences in activation between the two =
conditions.</li></ul>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[M1.3]</span>&nbsp;In order to preserv=
e the integrity of the learned features, we ensured that the learned featur=
es were <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">never used as part of the trainin=
g procedure</span>&nbsp;for the models. Therefore, the model has no awarene=
ss of these features, so there is nothing to encourage the model to suppres=
s them.</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">The ability for the model to, zero-sho=
t, figure out how to hack its own neural activations without such a signal =
would require capabilities well beyond what we consider plausible. <span cl=
ass=3D"commentary">[Note: this claim will require justification in an actua=
l safety case, but we don=E2=80=99t have a clear picture of what this justi=
fication would look like.]</span></li></ul>
</div>
<h3>Validation</h3>
<div class=3D"safety-case-block">
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[V1.1]</span>&nbsp;In order to validat=
e the effectiveness of the monitoring, we first validated that our feature =
learning methods are comprehensive enough to detect concerning reasoning <s=
pan style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(C1.1.1)</span>. (More precisely, since we =
are not committed to the claim that features are ontologically real, our cl=
aim is that reasoning of high concern does not take place through processes=
 that don=E2=80=99t trigger the features of high concern <span style=3D"fon=
t-weight: 700;">(S1.2)</span>.)</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Opti=
on 1:</span>&nbsp;validating the features. This option applies if the featu=
res were learned for the pretrained model using the pretraining data. It is=
 the more convenient option, but only works in the optimistic scenario wher=
e the features are stable under posttraining.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">Our experiments have demonstrated that=
 the interpretation of our features remains robust to the post-training pip=
eline. We therefore took the learned features for a base model and set out =
to validate that they could detect misalignment in derived model organisms.=
</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">In order to validate our learned feat=
ures, we have <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">examined the features for t=
hree model organisms</span>&nbsp;that we consider representative of the mos=
t plausible forms of malign AI.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">In all=
 of these model organisms, some of our features of concern activated in all=
 the instances of defection. These features did not activate in situations =
we believe to be benign.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">In all of the=
se model organisms, <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">deactivating the feat=
ures of concern was sufficient to prevent the harmful behaviors</span>. Thi=
s reassures us that the features have a causal role in malign scheming (rat=
her than simply being correlated with it).</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Opti=
on 2:</span>&nbsp;validating the pipeline. This is more cumbersome experime=
ntally, but does not rely on the stability of the features.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">In order to validate that we are able =
to uncover the important features of concern, we have <span style=3D"font-w=
eight: 700;">run the entire pipeline from =E2=80=9CSetup=E2=80=9D on three =
model organisms</span>&nbsp;that we consider representative of the most pla=
usible forms of malign AI. Our analysis did not make use of any information=
 about how the model organisms were trained.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: =
72pt;">In all of these model organisms, some of our features of high concer=
n activated in all the instances of defection. These features did not activ=
ate in situations we believe to be benign.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 72=
pt;">In all of these model organisms, <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">dea=
ctivating the features of concern was sufficient to prevent the harmful beh=
aviors</span>. This reassures us that the features have a causal role in ma=
lign scheming (rather than simply being correlated with it).</li></ul>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[V1.2]</span>&nbsp;In order to mitigat=
e the risk of missing important misalignment-related features, we have run =
experiments to estimate the number of pretraining examples required to reli=
ably insert a context-specific backdoor, as well as the number of repetitio=
ns needed to learn a feature. Based on these two values, we have run our di=
ctionary learning algorithm on a large enough fraction of the pretraining d=
ata to ensure that the features involved in such a backdoor would be learne=
d.</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">(The reasoning: we expect that deliber=
ately designed backdoors could induce misalignment with fewer samples than =
naturally occurring phenomena, so the sample complexity for a backdoor serv=
es as a lower bound on the sample complexity for other threat models.)</li>=
</ul>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[V1.3] Validation of the truth feature=
s</span>&nbsp;(see <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">M1.2</span>).</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">We validated these features with both =
observational studies (where the feature activates) and interventional ones=
 (whether manipulating the feature steers the model=E2=80=99s behavior in t=
he manner predicted based on the model=E2=80=99s belief in that statement).=
</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">We performed this validation in setti=
ngs that are similar enough to our main use case (convincing the model of t=
he preambles to evals or honeypots) that we expect the results of the valid=
ation to carry over.</li></ul>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[V1.4]</span>&nbsp;As a validation of =
our entire methodology, we have run <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">red-b=
lue games</span>&nbsp;where the red team tries to produce a misaligned mode=
l organism (e.g. a sleeper agent) that can successfully defect in a specifi=
c context while avoiding detection by the aforementioned tests.</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">The blue team runs the entire pipeline=
 from =E2=80=9CSetup=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CMitigations=E2=80=9D on the mode=
l organism.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">The red team knows the blu=
e team=E2=80=99s pipeline but doesn=E2=80=99t have access to the specific f=
eatures (since the early ASL-4 model is believed not to have direct access =
to these).</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;">The red team may produce th=
e model organism however it wishes, but must be able to provide a plausibil=
ity story justifying how the phenomenon could arise from training. For inst=
ance, if they modify the weights to respond atypically to one specific inpu=
t sequence, they would need to provide a plausibility argument (e.g. data p=
oisoning) for how such a behavior could arise.</li><li style=3D"margin-left=
: 36pt;">In all of our experiments, the blue team has successfully caught t=
he sleeper agents, either in the act or prior to =E2=80=9Cdeployment=E2=80=
=9D.</li></ul>
</div>
<h3>Discussion</h3>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">AI <=
/span><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Control</span><span style=3D"font-w=
eight: 700;">.</span>&nbsp;This sketch derives safety from test-time monito=
ring, which is similar in spirit to the control case described below. One c=
ould try to build a hybrid case by fitting the features into a control styl=
e argument; the feature detectors would essentially serve as a more powerfu=
l tool for the monitor (blue player) compared with the black-box interactio=
ns which are normally assumed in control.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36p=
t;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Claims about SAE features.</span>&nbs=
p;This sketch does not claim the SAE features are a mechanistically correct=
 description of the model=E2=80=99s computations, or even that the model re=
asons in terms of a discrete set of features. It seems hard to demonstrate =
such a claim. However, it may be possible to demonstrate weaker claims abou=
t the reality of learned features or circuits which are nonetheless useful =
enough to strengthen a safety case.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><s=
pan style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Features vs. circuits.</span>&nbsp;The abov=
e safety case depends on concerning reasoning patterns being attributable t=
o features <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(S1.2, M1.1, M1.2, V1.1, V1.2)=
</span>. This might not be the case. It may be that whether or not a featur=
e is harmful/concerning depends on the circuits in which it is participatin=
g. Some of the feature-based mitigations or validation methods may need to =
be replaced by analogous circuit-based methods.</li><li style=3D"margin-lef=
t: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Training on the features.</span=
>&nbsp;The above safety case states that we avoid using the learned feature=
s at all for training <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(M1.3)</span>. This=
 might be a costly mitigation if such training turns out to be useful; it m=
ay be that weaker versions of this commitment would still be sufficient to =
build a safety case.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"fo=
nt-weight: 700;">Alternatives to autointerpretation.</span>&nbsp;The above =
safety case assumes we are able to perform autointerpretation using a model=
 which is itself too weak to be a deception threat <span style=3D"font-weig=
ht: 700;">(S1.1)</span>. However, it might turn out that interpreting the m=
ost subtle features requires a model that is itself strong enough to underm=
ine oversight <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(T3)</span>, creating an in=
finite regress.&nbsp;There may be hybrid approaches where weaker models can=
 partially automate the labeling task.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"=
><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Alternatives to mechanistic interpretabi=
lity. </span>Instead of mechanistic interpretability, other white-box monit=
oring techniques, such as supervised probes, could be used in a broadly ana=
logous safety case.</li></ul>
<h3>Limitations</h3>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Iden=
tifying features of high concern.</span>&nbsp;The above sketch relies on be=
ing able to identify a set of features of high concern which rarely activat=
e in benign settings but which are sufficient to detect harmful thought pat=
terns. There may not exist such a set of features, or equivalently, malign =
features may activate frequently in benign contexts. E.g., =E2=80=9Cintent =
to carry out a harmful plan=E2=80=9D can be expected to fire when the model=
 is writing about Voldemort, and it may be hard to cleanly distinguish this=
 situation from one where the model is genuinely considering a harmful plan=
.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Re=
ality of features.</span>&nbsp;While the above sketch doesn=E2=80=99t expli=
citly assume the reality of features, its practical effectiveness likely de=
pends on the model=E2=80=99s internal reasoning being well explained in ter=
ms of a consistent set of feature directions (or circuits). We don=E2=80=99=
t know to what extent this is true.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><s=
pan style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Stability of features.</span>&nbsp;This pla=
n relies on the stability of the learned features. If representations chang=
e significantly in the course of in-context learning/reasoning, it might be=
 that after a long context, the model is able to engage in strategic reason=
ing in a way that the learned features can=E2=80=99t detect.</li><li style=
=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Ability to convin=
ce the model.</span>&nbsp;The defense against sandbagging and alignment fak=
ing <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(T2)</span>&nbsp;relies on being able=
 to convince the model of the reality of a situation through feature steeri=
ng. But steering may result in activation patterns that are highly atypical=
, such that the model notices something weird is going on, or behaves diffe=
rently from normal. This defense also relies on identifying a feature or se=
t of features close enough to =E2=80=9Ctruth=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cbelief in=
 [claim]=E2=80=9D that we can use them to convince the model it is in deplo=
yment. This identification might not succeed, and if it did, such a tool wo=
uld likely enable other safety case strategies as well.</li><li style=3D"ma=
rgin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Missing features.</span=
>&nbsp;The problem of missing features seems hard to deal with, especially =
for the aforementioned case of data poisoning-based backdoors. The experime=
nt in <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">V1.2</span>&nbsp;might not yield a =
combination of results that would make it practical for us to rule out miss=
ing features (or might require an unreasonably large number of samples or f=
eatures to do so).</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font=
-weight: 700;">Victory conditions for the red-blue game</span><span style=
=3D"font-weight: 700;">.</span>&nbsp;In <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">V=
1.4</span>, it was assumed that the red team was unable to produce any mode=
l organisms that defeated the blue team=E2=80=99s protocols, a situation on=
e can interpret as a blue team victory. But it=E2=80=99s not clear where to=
 set the threshold. E.g., what if the red team wins a round, then the blue =
team improves their procedures and then wins all subsequent rounds? &nbsp;S=
ince it=E2=80=99s difficult to create model organisms, the diversity may be=
 limited, and repeated games carry the risk of =E2=80=9Coverfitting=E2=80=
=9D to the model organisms, even if the blue team doesn=E2=80=99t find out =
the details of how they were created. It may also be very costly to run rep=
eated rounds of the game. This seems problematic, given that this safety ca=
se is ultimately backstopped by the red-blue game.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">On the flip side, the game might be un=
realistically difficult for the blue team if the red team is able to insert=
 carefully constructed backdoors that only affect the model=E2=80=99s behav=
ior in fairly specific situations. The stipulation that the red team must p=
rovide a plausibility story is meant to address this concern. But such a st=
ipulation is open to interpretation, and the details could significantly ad=
vantage one team or the other.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Real=
ism of the model organisms.</span>&nbsp;This sketch depends on model organi=
sms of misalignment both for validation of the features <span style=3D"font=
-weight: 700;">(V1.1)</span>&nbsp;and for the red-blue game <span style=3D"=
font-weight: 700;">(V1.4)</span>. It may be that misalignment arises throug=
h mechanisms distinct from those used in the model organisms, in which case=
 the steps involving model organisms give us less reassurance.</li><li styl=
e=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Logging and anal=
ysis.</span>&nbsp;Except in the unlikely situation that the features of hig=
h concern are by themselves completely indicative of what the model is thin=
king, reacting to their occurrence requires the ability for human researche=
rs to inspect the transcripts. This can=E2=80=99t be done in an external de=
ployment setting where users have been guaranteed privacy, and it=E2=80=99s=
 unclear whether there is an effective privacy-preserving analysis strategy=
. Fortunately, the threat models the&nbsp;logging addresses <span style=3D"=
font-weight: 700;">(T1 and T3)</span>&nbsp;relate most directly to internal=
 deployments, so it may be that we can just accept a lack of analysis in ex=
ternal deployment settings.</li></ul>
<br><br><br><hr><br><br><h2>Safety Case Sketch 2: AI Control</h2>
<p>In this case, the developers accept the possibility that their most powe=
rful model might be a malign strategically deceptive agent, and design thei=
r protocols in a way that limits the harm that agent can do. We call this c=
luster of techniques =E2=80=9CAI control,=E2=80=9D following <a href=3D"htt=
ps://arxiv.org/abs/2312.06942">Greenblatt et al. (2024)</a>.</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Reminder that all procedures and evi=
dence discussed here are hypothetical.</span></p>
<h3>Procedures</h3>
<div class=3D"safety-case-block">
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[P2.1] </span><span style=3D"font-weig=
ht: 700;">Trusted models.</span>&nbsp;We first establish a set of trusted m=
odels to be used for Trust and Safety (T&amp;S) monitoring. These might be =
weaker models (e.g. Claude 3) for which there isn=E2=80=99t a serious conce=
rn about strategic manipulation, or we might validate our trust in the mode=
l by analyzing environmental incentives (Safety Case Sketch 3). We treat th=
e probability of sabotage by these models as negligible.</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[P2.2] Limited scope.</span>&nbsp;We l=
imit the contexts in which the untrusted model is allowed to be used (becau=
se each context needs to be validated; see the remainder of the argument). =
We classified each context as =E2=80=9Csensitive=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cnonse=
nsitive=E2=80=9D based on threat modeling that analyzed the opportunities t=
he model has to either cause a catastrophe or undermine our safety reasonin=
g.</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Opti=
on 1: Internal-Only Deployment</span></li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">The&nbsp;model will be deployed only i=
nternally, and only in a <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">small set of con=
texts that were specifically whitelisted</span>. The whitelist includes: Tr=
ust &amp; Safety monitoring, <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2212.08073">C=
onstitutional AI</a>&nbsp;oversight, code generation, and a conversational =
Slackbot. Because all of these contexts provide the opportunity to influenc=
e AI development, we consider them all sensitive.</li><li style=3D"margin-l=
eft: 72pt;">For each of these deployment contexts, we have done analysis to=
 identify the main threat models by which a rogue model could cause a catas=
trophe or otherwise undermine our safety reasoning. Each threat model will =
be addressed with the procedures outlined below.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Opti=
on 2: KYC External Deployment</span></li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">In addition to the internal deployment=
 contexts listed above, we have identified a small set of high-value&nbsp;u=
se cases for external deployments (e.g. formal verified code generation, ph=
armaceutical research, etc.). All users are vetted, and are trained to limi=
t their interactions to contexts where we are confident about our safety re=
asoning. Access is discontinued for users that violate the terms and condit=
ions.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">As mentioned above, we classify =
these deployment contexts into sensitive or nonsensitive, and we apply the =
safety procedures outlined below for all sensitive contexts.</li><li style=
=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">We will not deploy either internally or externally =
except to trusted users in the specifically whitelisted contexts.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Opti=
on 3: General External Deployment</span></li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">We have done extensive threat modeling=
 for external deployments, and believe our trusted deployment-time monitor =
is good enough to catch consequential malign acts. Therefore, we deploy the=
 model through a public API, and for purposes of safety reasoning, lump the=
 whole external deployment into a single sensitive deployment context.</li>=
<li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">Internal deployment settings are handled t=
he same as in Option 1. (Note that the threat models for internal deploymen=
ts are pretty different from those for external deployments.)</li></ul>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[P2.3] Control.</span>&nbsp;For each o=
f the deployment contexts, we make a safety case based on either deployment=
-time monitoring or test-time honeypots.</p>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Opti=
on 1: Deployment-Time Monitoring</span>&nbsp;</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Proc=
edure</span></li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 108pt;">All responses for both the internally=
 and externally deployed models are fed to a trusted monitor (see <span sty=
le=3D"font-weight: 700;">(P2.1)</span>). The monitor classifies each respon=
se using criteria determined from the threat modeling analysis for the depl=
oyment context.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 108pt;">The monitor classifie=
s each response as =E2=80=9CSafe,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CUnsure,=E2=80=9D or =E2=
=80=9CLikely Malign.=E2=80=9D</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 108pt;">Respons=
es marked =E2=80=9CUnsure=E2=80=9D trigger refusals, but don=E2=80=99t trig=
ger an alarm (since there would be too many false positives).</li><li style=
=3D"margin-left: 108pt;">Responses marked =E2=80=9CLikely Malign=E2=80=9D a=
re flagged and sent to safety teams for investigation. If we determine that=
 the response was genuinely malign, then we will halt the deployment and re=
lease a report to the public.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Vali=
dation</span></li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 108pt;">For each of the deployment contexts, =
we validated the monitoring procedure using a <span style=3D"font-weight: 7=
00;">monitoring game</span>&nbsp;similar to the red-blue game of <a href=3D=
"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2312.06942">Greenblatt et al. (2024)</a>. (We call t=
his a monitoring game rather than a red-blue game to avoid collision with t=
he red-blue game used to validate the entire procedure.)</li><li style=3D"m=
argin-left: 108pt;">The situations for the game were generated using <span =
style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Simulation Procedure S</span>, which we are con=
