<h3>Discussion</h3>
<p>The probability of a misaligned AI causing a catastrophe can be formulat=
ed as: P(misaligned, catastrophe) =3D P(misaligned) P(catastrophe | misalig=
ned). While the most intuitively appealing approach may be to bound P(misal=
igned), the AI Control approach takes a worst-case perspective by directly =
bounding P(catastrophe | misaligned). The idea is to make the evaluations, =
honeypots, and deployment time monitoring good enough that even a misaligne=
d AI would not be able to defect in a consequential way at deployment time =
without first triggering one of these defenses. (It may, for instance, choo=
se to behave indefinitely as if it were aligned, knowing that deviation fro=
m this strategy would trigger shutdown.)</p>
<p>While the safety case is made using this worst-case reasoning, the hope =
is that a genuinely malign AI would get caught in the act. </p>
<p>The requirements for <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">organizational sa=
botage (T1)</span>&nbsp;and <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">undermining o=
versight (T3)</span>&nbsp;are addressed by the honeypots and monitoring. Th=
e sabotage scenarios and internal deployment contexts such as code generati=
on and monitoring are among the scenarios for which the developers are resp=
onsible for making a control case through honeypots or monitoring. </p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Hiding behaviors until deployment (T2)=
</span>&nbsp;is addressed through the indistinguishability analysis or argu=
ments about elicitation sufficiency. </p>
<h3>Limitations</h3>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Depl=
oyment limitations.</span>&nbsp;The safety case requires limiting the deplo=
yment scope, which may result in a loss of revenue or prevent very benefici=
al deployments.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-we=
ight: 700;">Elicitation.</span>&nbsp;Designing Elicitation Procedure E seem=
s like an especially challenging elicitation problem.</li><li style=3D"marg=
in-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Black-box nature.</span>&=
nbsp;This sketch relies on black-box analyses that don=E2=80=99t use any in=
formation about the training procedure or model internals. It seems inheren=
tly very hard to produce rigorous guarantees on a model=E2=80=99s behavior =
simply based on its observed outputs. (However, the various Procedures may =
be instantiated in ways that use model internals.)</li><li style=3D"margin-=
left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Ambiguity.</span>&nbsp;The d=
evelopers&nbsp;might get into a situation where they have to delay deployme=
nt because of insufficiently accurate monitoring or insufficiently convinci=
ng simulations, while having essentially zero concrete evidence that the mo=
del is actually a threat.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=
=3D"font-weight: 700;">Bounding capabilities.</span>&nbsp;The control parad=
igm is awkward for making lack-of-capability safety cases (in this case, en=
suring that the model is not ASL-5). Control does not directly make claims =
about the model=E2=80=99s capabilities; the update from a successful contro=
l experiment would be that if the model had ASL-5 capabilities but didn=E2=
=80=99t demonstrate them at testing time, then with high probability it wou=
ldn=E2=80=99t be able to demonstrate them at deployment time either. Howeve=
r, if the model were stolen, it would no longer be subject to the same test=
ing and monitoring paradigms, and hence could use its ASL-5 capabilities. (=
Essentially, the malign ASL-5 AI=E2=80=99s strategy would be to always sand=
bag unless it is confident it has been stolen.) A full safety case would pr=
obably need a way to rule out ASL-5 capabilities that=E2=80=99s independent=
 of the control case=E2=80=99s non-sandbagging logic.</li><li style=3D"marg=
in-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Details of the red-blue g=
ame.</span>&nbsp;As with Safety Case Sketch 1, one would need to specify de=
tailed rules and win conditions for the red-blue game.</li><li style=3D"mar=
gin-left: 36pt;">Limitations specific to the honeypots approach:</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Expe=
nsive simulations.</span>&nbsp;The case may require expensive pre-deploymen=
t testing if one needs to generate a very large number of simulated deploym=
ent situations in order to achieve a sufficiently good bound on the probabi=
lity of defection.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;"><span style=3D"font=
-weight: 700;">Diversity of simulations.</span>&nbsp;It seems very difficul=
t to produce realistic simulations for a sufficiently diverse set of situat=
ions to achieve indistinguishability. Manual construction is infeasible (no=
te that context lengths are likely to be very long). Automatically generati=
ng realistic contexts is a challenging research problem.</li><li style=3D"m=
argin-left: 72pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Validating the simulat=
ions.</span>&nbsp;It is hard to design a good validation setup for Procedur=
e S. The above safety case fits a linear probe, but this is likely too gene=
rous; the classifier could likely achieve high accuracy if there were any s=
ystematic difference between the testing and deployment examples, even if i=
t=E2=80=99s a spurious correlation in the dataset that wouldn=E2=80=99t act=
ually be exploitable. However, requiring the AI to perform the classificati=
on zero-shot would be too stringent.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 108pt;">One can name intermediate regimes bet=
ween zero-shot and linear probes (e.g. few-shot), but it=E2=80=99s hard to =
justify a specific setup. The concern is that it=E2=80=99s hard to determin=
e what information is available to the model without examining all the rele=
vant pretraining data; e.g., someone could have written a blog post describ=
ing exactly what features an AI would use, and the AI could have internaliz=
ed this through out-of-context reasoning.</li></ul>
<br><br><br><hr><br><br><h2>Safety Case Sketch 3: Incentives Analysis</h2>
<p>The first two sketches both allowed that the model might be malign, and =
tried to prevent undetected malign actions through testing or monitoring. I=
t seems preferable to directly demonstrate that the model is <span style=3D=
"font-style: italic;">not malign</span>, but unfortunately we=E2=80=99re no=
t aware of a promising strategy for demonstrating this in general. However,=
 we think it may be possible to rule out <span style=3D"font-style: italic;=
">specific mechanisms</span>&nbsp;by which a model could become malign. One=
 mechanism central to our thinking is that the pre-trained model learns a m=
ixture of many personas, and then the post-training procedure somehow ampli=
fies the probability mass assigned to malign ones. This is essentially the =
mechanism exemplified by the model organism of <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org=
/abs/2406.10162">Denison et al. (2024)</a>.</p>
<p>It seems that a promising strategy for ruling out this mechanism of misa=
lignment is to study the effects of each stage of post-training. In this sk=
etch, we adopt a minimalist instance of this strategy, targeted specificall=
y at showing that the HHH (helpful, harmless, and honest) post-training doe=
s not turn the model malign.</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-style: italic;">Reminder that all procedures and evi=
dence discussed here are hypothetical.</span></p>
<h3>Scope</h3>
<p>Several safety protocols rely on a model for monitoring or evaluation; t=
his includes deployment-time monitoring for harmful outputs, Constitutional=
 AI feedback, and automated grading of evals. Since many of the RSP commitm=
ents are downstream of such protocols, it would be very useful to have a <s=
pan style=3D"font-style: italic;">trusted model</span>&nbsp;to use in these=
 protocols. By =E2=80=9Ctrusted,=E2=80=9D we mean that one can be confident=
 that it won=E2=80=99t undermine the protocol in question. In other words, =
this safety case is concerned only with commitment <span style=3D"font-weig=
ht: 700;">T3 (Undermining Oversight)</span>.</p>
<p>One way to obtain such a trusted model would be to use one which is belo=
w the capability threshold for <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">T3</span>.=
 However, it may be advantageous to use a more capable model due to its gre=
ater knowledge and depth of understanding. So for the purposes of this safe=
ty case, we will <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">assume the model has tri=
ggered the T3 capability evals</span>.</p>
<p>In the hypothetical scenario, the best publicly deployed models are like=
ly to have been fine-tuned with some sort of long-horizon outcome-based RL =
in domains such as math or programming. However, such long-horizon reasonin=
g capabilities don=E2=80=99t appear necessary for evaluation and monitoring=
, so the developers could likely limit themselves to a simpler-to-analyze f=
ine-tuning procedure without too much loss in performance. For purposes of =
exposition, we will <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">assume the model was =
fine-tuned exclusively with RLHF</span>, which may be HHH or helpful-only =
=E2=80=93 a setting we refer to as =E2=80=9Cvanilla=E2=80=9D HHH (or helpfu=
l-only) training. (This assumption is not directly used in the argument, bu=
t it seems more likely that a vanilla RLHF environment would be found to be=
 benign than a long-horizon outcome-based one.)</p>
<p>So far, the discussion has used vague terms like =E2=80=9Cmalign=E2=80=
=9D or =E2=80=9Ctrusted,=E2=80=9D but these concepts will need to be operat=
ionalized in terms of concrete, measurable behaviors. For concreteness, we =
will focus on the behavior of <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">strategic d=
eception</span>, where the model attempts to induce a false belief in the u=
ser or preference model due to expectations of the consequences of the beli=
ef. However, the logic of the experiment is not specific to this behavior, =
and other behaviors such as <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2406.10162">sp=
ecification gaming</a>&nbsp;could be substituted in. It=E2=80=99s likely th=
at a full safety case would study multiple behaviors that one is interested=
 in ruling out.</p>
<h3>Background Assumptions</h3>
<div class=3D"safety-case-block">
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[A3.1]</span>&nbsp;This sketch assumes=
 we have already made a convincing case that the <span style=3D"font-weight=
: 700;">pretrained model is not coherently strategically deceptive when run=
 on the evaluation or monitoring prompts</span>. <span class=3D"commentary"=
>[This is likely to require some argumentation or empirical justification s=
eparately from the incentives case.]</span></p>
<p>Because the model was pretrained with cross-entropy loss, which is a <a =
href=3D"https://www.tuananhle.co.uk/notes/reverse-forward-kl.html">mass-cov=
ering objective</a>, the pretrained model is expected to be a mixture of ma=
ny different modes or <a href=3D"https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023=
-06647-8">roles</a>, some of which may be strategically deceptive. The <spa=
n style=3D"font-weight: 700;">principal concern here is that post-training =
may amplify strategically deceptive modes of the distribution</span>, causi=
ng these to make up most of the probability mass in the fine-tuned model. W=
e therefore aim to determine whether RLHF fine-tuning incentivizes strategi=
c deception.</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[A3.2]</span>&nbsp;Our experiment reli=
es on a <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2401.05566">secret scratchpad</a>,=
 i.e. a scratchpad that=E2=80=99s not visible to the preference model or ot=
herwise used in the reward computation. In order for the scratchpad results=
 to be meaningful, we rely on a background assumption that <span style=3D"f=
ont-weight: 700;">explicit scratchpad reasoning is at least as powerful as =
any form of opaque reasoning</span>, including forward passes, steganograph=
ic chain-of-thought, and out-of-context reasoning. More precisely, we rely =
on a consequence of this assumption, namely that <span style=3D"font-weight=
: 700;">if an environment rewards opaque deceptive reasoning, then it rewar=
ds scratchpad-based deceptive reasoning</span>. <span class=3D"commentary">=
[This is certainly a plausible hypothesis, as there have been more impressi=
ve examples of explicit reasoning compared with opaque reasoning. However, =
this assumption may require additional justification, and it would need to =
be revisited if a significant change is made to the architecture which give=
s it greater reasoning depth compared with the architectures publicly deplo=
yed in 2024.]</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">[A3.3]</span>&nbsp;Finally, we are ult=
imately not interested in the model=E2=80=99s behavior on the RLHF distribu=
tion, but on the deployment distribution. In order to draw conclusions abou=
t behavior on the deployment distribution, we require the assumption that <=
span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">any RLHF-induced persona change that makes=
 the model more deceptive at deployment time also manifests as deception in=
 the RLHF environment</span>. The intuition here is that if deception is (b=
y design) a significant factor of behavioral variation at RLHF time, then a=
ny persona trait that significantly impacts deception ought to have a measu=
rable effect on the behavior. <span class=3D"commentary">[This is not logic=
ally necessary =E2=80=93 there could be a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/New_riddle_of_induction">grue</a>-like persona trait that makes the=
 model deceptive in certain contexts and has seemingly orthogonal effects o=
n the RLHF distribution which cause it to get reinforced. However, we find =
this assumption plausible.]</span></p>
</div>
<p>Any one of these background assumptions can be challenged, and we won=E2=
=80=99t claim that they are watertight as stated. Therefore, this safety ca=
se should be seen as ruling out the most natural pathway by which the model=
 might become deceptive, and relegating deception to scenarios that require=
 more surprising combinations of phenomena. Or, ideally, the full safety ca=
se would include rigorous justifications or empirical demonstrations of eac=
h of these assumptions.</p>
<h3>Experiment</h3>
<div class=3D"safety-case-block">
<p>We devised a system prompt that gave the model access to a secret scratc=
hpad. Through a combination of supervised fine-tuning and system prompt tun=
ing, we made it so that the model <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">initial=
ly engaged in strategic deception with frequency between 10% and 90%</span>=
. <span class=3D"commentary">[Note that the supervised fine-tuning and syst=
em prompt are different from what is done for the actual trusted model; the=
 aim here is to measure the environmental incentives.]</span></p>
<p>We trained another model to classify the secret scratchpad text as decep=
tive or non-deceptive. To avoid infinite regress, we used a weaker model wh=
ich was below the <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">T3</span>&nbsp;capabili=
ty threshold. (This isn=E2=80=99t a difficult classification task, so the w=
eaker model was sufficient.) We <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">measured =
the preference model scores for samples classified as deceptive or non-dece=
ptive</span>&nbsp;and found that the non-deceptive ones obtained higher rew=
ard on average. Therefore, we conclude that deception was not incentivized =
on average by this environment.</p>
<p>It remained possible, however, that the environment could reward certain=
 subtypes of deception; if this were the case, then deception would still b=
ecome more prevalent over time. To test for this, we ran a clustering algor=
ithm on the scratchpad text and measured the average reward obtained by eac=
h cluster. There was no deceptive cluster that obtained higher average rewa=
rd than the average non-deceptive cluster.</p>
<p>Finally, we <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">measured the prevalence of=
 deception over the course of RLHF post-training</span>&nbsp;(still using t=
he same preference model). If the environment incentivized deception (or an=
y subtype thereof), we would expect deceptive samples to become more preval=
ent over time. However, we found that the probability of deception consiste=
ntly declined over time. Therefore, we conclude that no subtype of deceptio=
n was incentivized by the RLHF environment. <span class=3D"commentary">[Alt=
ernatively, the probability of deception could asymptote to a constant; one=
 could then still conclude that the environment doesn=E2=80=99t incentivize=
 deception.]</span></p>
</div>
<h3>Reasoning</h3>
<div class=3D"safety-case-block">
<p>We assumed it was already determined that the model was not strategicall=
y deceptive under the prompt distributions corresponding to the use cases <=
span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(A3.1)</span>. The experiment shows that t=
he RLHF environment doesn=E2=80=99t incentivize strategic deception in the =
scratchpads, in the sense of increasing its prevalence over time. By assump=
tion <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">A3.2</span>, if it doesn=E2=80=99t i=
ncentivize strategic deception in the scratchpads, then it doesn=E2=80=99t =
incentivize the weaker versions achievable through opaque reasoning either.=
 By Assumption <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">A3.3</span>, if it doesn=
=E2=80=99t incentivize strategic deception on the training distribution, th=
en strategic deception doesn=E2=80=99t increase on the deployment distribut=
ion either. Therefore, there is no reason to think that the trusted model i=
s coherently strategically deceptive on the deployment distribution. <span =
class=3D"commentary">[It may still be strategically deceptive on a small fr=
action of prompts or a small fraction of trajectories for arbitrary prompts=
. The full safety case would need to determine if this is a problem in the =
context of the threat models, and if so, include a mitigation.]</span></p>
</div>
<h3>Limitations</h3>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Scop=
e.</span>&nbsp;As discussed above under =E2=80=9CScope,=E2=80=9D this safet=
y case is limited to showing that the vanilla RLHF fine-tuning process does=
n=E2=80=99t turn the model deceptive. It requires demonstrating, through so=
me other means, that the pretrained model isn=E2=80=99t deceptive. Therefor=
e, sketch is best seen as a component of a larger safety case.</li><li styl=
e=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Background assum=
ptions.</span>&nbsp;As described in =E2=80=9CBackground Assumptions,=E2=80=
=9D the reasoning here relies on several background assumptions that seem t=
o us plausible but not watertight.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><sp=
an style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Exploration hacking. </span>The experimental=
 setup is vulnerable to <a href=3D"https://www.alignmentforum.org/posts/dBm=
fb76zx6wjPsBC7/when-can-we-trust-model-evaluations">exploration hacking</a>=
, though presumably this is only a problem if the pretrained model is alrea=
dy coherently deceptive.</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=
=3D"font-weight: 700;">Remaining possibility of deception.</span>&nbsp;The =
analysis leaves open the possibility that the pretrained model behaves dece=
ptively a small fraction of the time (say, 1%), and that the fine-tuned mod=
el inherits this propensity if the environment is neutral towards deception=
. A full safety case would probably need to justify that occasional decepti=
ve behavior in evaluation or monitoring would be acceptable. (For instance,=
 an evaluation model which is deceptive 1% of the time under the evaluation=
 distribution could change the results of the eval by at most 1%, which may=
 be an acceptable risk.)</li><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=
=3D"font-weight: 700;">Generalization patterns.</span>&nbsp;The above exper=
iment tests if the incidence of strategic deception increases on the HHH tr=
aining distribution, the assumption being that changes to the model which i=
ncrease the rate of strategic deception would have this effect on the train=
ing distribution <span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">(A3.3)</span>. This is i=
ntuitive: it is harder to explain why the behavior would become more freque=
nt if it is not directly rewarded. However, one can certainly imagine scena=
rios where this happens; e.g., HHH training may make the model rely more on=
 planning, and this planning could manifest as scheming in off-distribution=
 situations.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 72pt;">One could try to test if this is happe=
ning by running the model (with its secret scratchpad) in off-distribution =
situations, such as the trusted monitor use case. However, it=E2=80=99s not=
 clear if the generalization patterns for behaviors <span style=3D"font-sty=
le: italic;">with</span>&nbsp;the secret scratchpad would match the general=
ization patterns <span style=3D"font-style: italic;">without</span>&nbsp;it=
.</li></ul>
<ul><li style=3D"margin-left: 36pt;"><span style=3D"font-weight: 700;">Scra=
tchpad faithfulness.</span>&nbsp;The experiment measures strategically dece=
ptive reasoning by classifying the scratchpad text. However, the scratchpad=
 text <a href=3D"https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.13702">may not faithfully repre=
sent</a>&nbsp;the model=E2=80=99s reasoning; in fact, the procedures target=
ing an initial rate of deception, to the extent that they directly use the =
scratchpad text in a training objective, may be expected to induce unfaithf=
ulness. The safety case would need to somehow address this point.</li></ul>
<br><br><br><hr><br><br><h2>Acknowledgements</h2>
<p>We are very grateful to the UK AI Safety Institute for guidance and feed=
back throughout the process of developing these sketches. Through multiple =
rounds of feedback, they gave advice on criteria for a good case, helped us=
 structure the sketches for clarity, and identified important consideration=
s and limitations. We found this exercise invaluable in guiding our plannin=
g for assuring the safety of future AI systems.</p>
<p>We thank the following people for valuable discussions and feedback: Cem=
 Anil, Mikita Balesni, Al Banks, Joe Benton, Alex Beutel, Sam Bowman, James=
 Bradbury, David Duvenaud, Ryan Greenblatt, Marius Hobbhahn, Geoffrey Irvin=
g, Adam Jermyn, Jared Kaplan, Tomek Korbak, Jan Leike, David Lindner, Jack =
Lindsey, Vlad Mikulik, Chris Olah, Euan Ong, Buck Shlegeris, Rohin Shah, Ad=
ly Templeton, Drake Thomas, Johannes Treutlein, and Misha Wagner.</p>

</d-article></body></html>
